## Summary of Key Design Changes

### Revision 5.0 Updates (Current - v5.0)

**Atmos Speaker Upgrade: DIYSG Volt-10**

**Previous design (Rev 4.2):**
- DIY Eminence-based build (Beta-8CX woofer, PSD:2002S-8 compression driver)
- 8" woofer, 0.6 cubic foot cabinet
- Estimated sensitivity: 95-97 dB
- Performance at MLP: 104-105 dB (marginal for THX Reference 105 dB requirement)
- Cost: ~$200 per speaker, $1,220 total for 6

**Current design (Revision 5.0):**
- DIYSG Volt-10 (optimized for home theater reference systems)
- 10" woofer, verified 98 dB sensitivity
- Performance at MLP: 107-108 dB (exceeds THX Reference by +2-3 dB)
- Cost: ~$350-400 per speaker, $2,100-2,400 total for 6

**Benefits of Revision 5.0 Changes:**

**Performance:**
- **Guaranteed reference capability:** 107-108 dB at both seating rows vs. marginal 104-105 dB
- **+3 dB headroom:** Comfortable dynamic range for demanding Atmos soundtracks
- **Verified specifications:** 98 dB sensitivity measured by DIYSG (not estimated)
- **Better midbass:** 10" woofer provides superior authority for Atmos effects

**System Integration:**
- **Eliminates weak link:** All channels now reference-capable (LCR, surrounds, subs, Atmos)
- **Consistent philosophy:** Matches the no-compromise approach of rest of system
- **Proven design:** DIYSG engineering removes guesswork from DIY approach

**Value:**
- **Cost increase:** +$880-1,180 total ($146-196 per speaker)
- **Performance gain:** +3 dB SPL capability, verified specifications
- **Appropriate scaling:** In context of $68K+ system, ensures no performance compromises

**Rationale:**
With subwoofers exceeding THX Reference by +8 dB and LCR/surrounds all reference-capable, having marginal Atmos channels would be the system's limiting factor. The Volt-10 ensures consistent reference-level performance across all channels, matching the system's overall philosophy.

**Material costs:** Net increase of +$880-1,180 total system cost
- Atmos speakers: +$880-1,180 (DIYSG Volt-10 vs. DIY Eminence)
- Benefit: Guaranteed reference performance, no weak links

---

### Revision 4.1 Updates

**3" Recessed Driver Mounting with Integrated AT Fabric Covers:**

**Previous design (Rev 4.0):**
- Front subs: 45"W × 21"H × 24"D with flat front baffle
- Rear subs: 24"W × 42"H × 22"D with flat front baffle 
- Corner pockets: 45" wide
- Center section: 102" wide
- Drivers mounted flush to front baffle
- Separate AT fabric panels on stage front
- Clearance above front subs: 6"

**Current design (Revision 4.1):**
- Front subs: 51"W × 27"H × 24"D with 3" recessed driver mounting
- Rear subs: 30"W × 48"H × 22"D with 3" recessed driver mounting
- Corner pockets: 51" wide (accommodates larger width)
- Center section: 90" wide (adjusted for pocket expansion)
- Drivers recessed 3" behind perimeter frame
- Integrated AT fabric covers (51"W × 27"H front, 30"W × 48"H rear)
- Clearance above front subs: 0" (exact fit - 27" sub in 27" pocket)

**Benefits of Revision 4.1 Changes:**

**Protection & Aesthetics:**
- Professional driver protection: 3" recessed mounting shields all 8 drivers
- Integrated covers: Self-contained subwoofer assemblies (enclosure + cover)
- Commercial-grade appearance: Recessed drivers with AT fabric
- Prevents accidental cone damage during installation and use

**Construction & Service:**
- Simpler stage design: Eliminates separate stage front AT panel system
- Modular assemblies: Build subs complete with covers in workshop
- Easier service: Remove individual covers vs. removing stage panels
- Improved access: Direct access to recessed drivers through integrated covers

**Acoustic:**
- Maintains identical internal volume (~8-9 ft³ per enclosure)
- Same Qtc alignment (0.91) and performance characteristics
- No change to SPL capability (109 dB @ 20Hz at MLP)
- 3" air gap prevents fabric pumping (acoustic transparency maintained)

**Practical:**
- Exact fit: 27" tall front subs in 27" tall pockets (no wasted space)
- Professional installation: Subs install as complete units
- Front/rear subs still use matching volumes (Dirac ART compatibility)
- Consistent driver protection approach (all four subs identical concept)

**Material costs:** Net increase of +$268 total system cost
- Front subs: +$145 (larger enclosures, integrated covers)
- Rear subs: +$330 (larger enclosures, integrated covers) 
- Stage platform: +$13 (larger corner pockets)
- Eliminated: -$220 (separate stage front AT panels)

---

### Revision 4.0 Updates

**Subwoofer Dimension Optimization:**

**Previous design (Rev 3):**
- Front subs: 42"W × 24"H × 24"D horizontal
- Rear subs: 24"W × 42"H × 24"D vertical
- Corner pockets: 42" wide
- Center section: 108" wide
- Clearance above front subs: 3"

**Previous design (Revision 4.0):**
- Front subs: 45"W × 21"H × 24"D horizontal (optimized dimensions)
- Rear subs: 24"W × 42"H × 22"D vertical (matched volume)
- Corner pockets: 45" wide (accommodates larger width)
- Center section: 102" wide (adjusted for pocket expansion)
- Clearance above front subs: 6" (improved serviceability)

**Benefits of Revision 4 Changes:**

**Construction:**
- Better driver spacing: 4.5" between driver edges vs. 3-4" previously
- Improved front baffle rigidity (less extreme aspect ratio)
- More practical height (21" vs. 24" - easier to maneuver during construction)
- Better top clearance (6" vs. 3" - easier cable routing)

**Acoustic:**
- Maintains identical internal volume (~8 ft’³³ per enclosure)
- Same Qtc alignment (0.91) and performance characteristics
- No change to calculated SPL capability (109 dB @ 20Hz at MLP)

**Practical:**
- Front/rear subs use matching volumes (important for Dirac ART)
- Rear subs 2" shallower (22"D vs. 24"D - saves floor space)
- Still fits all stage constraints (45" < 48" available corner width)
- Better use of available space

**Material costs:** Minimal change (~$11 additional for slightly larger corner pockets and openings)

---

### Revision 3 Updates

**WinISD Pro Verification:**
- All Dayton Audio UMII18-22 Thiele-Small parameters confirmed in WinISD Pro software
- Dual-driver sealed enclosure configuration (4.5 ft³ per driver) modeled and verified
- Qtc alignment (0.91), F3 response (~38 Hz), and impedance characteristics validated
- Power handling and excursion behavior at 225W per driver confirmed safe
- Box resonance frequency (Fc = 37.8 Hz) matches hand calculations
- Software modeling provides additional confidence in the sealed alignment design

### Revision 2 Updates

### Front Stage Reconfiguration

**Previous design:**
- Solid stage platform (16' ’ 30')
- Consideration of equipment bay under stage OR side rack placement

**Previous design (Revision 2, updated in Rev 4.0, now Rev 4.1):**
- Three-zone stage: Corner sub pockets + center solid section
- Equipment rack ON stage deck (beside LCR speakers)
- Front subwoofers on FLOOR in corner pockets (under stage deck)
- Horizontal sub orientation (45"W × 21"H × 24"D - optimized in Rev 4)

### Equipment Placement

**Previous consideration:**
- Under-stage equipment bay with slide-out shelves
- OR side rack beside stage (freestanding)

**Current design (Revision 2):**
- 42U rack on stage deck (center solid section)
- Positioned beside left speaker
- Access through false wall AT fabric panel (removable)
- Standing access (superior to under-stage)

### Front Subwoofer Integration

**Previous design:**
- Front subs in room corners, beside stage (freestanding)
- OR under stage with complex access

**Previous design (Revision 2, dimensions optimized in Rev 4.1):**
- Front subs integrated into stage structure (floor-level corner pockets)
- Horizontal orientation fits under 27" deck (21" tall + 6" clearance - Rev 4)
- No protrusion into room (24" depth within 30" stage)
- Fire through openings in stage front (covered by AT fabric panels)
- Full three-wall corner loading maintained
- Completely hidden installation

### Benefits of Revision 2 Design

**Acoustic:**
- All four subs achieve three-wall corner loading (+12-15 dB at 20Hz)
- Symmetric front sub placement (optimal for Dirac ART)
- No compromise in boundary reinforcement

**Practical:**
- Simplified stage construction (no complex equipment bay)
- Superior equipment access (standing vs. floor panels)
- Protected subwoofer installation (enclosed in structure)
- Short cable runs (rack to LCR: inches, rack to subs: feet)

**Aesthetic:**
- Everything hidden (subs under deck, rack behind panel)
- Clean stage front (AT fabric panels match screen)
- Professional cinema appearance
- Consistent design (all subs behind AT fabric)

**Cost:**
- Similar or lower total cost
- Simpler construction = less labor
- No complex slide mechanisms or access panels

